Certainly! Automating the selection of all checkboxes on a webpage and then saving them can be achieved using JavaScript. Below is an example of how you might do this:

1. **Select all checkboxes**: Use `document.querySelectorAll` to get all the checkboxes.
2. **Check all checkboxes**: Loop through each checkbox and set its `checked` property to `true`.
3. **Trigger the save action**: If there's a specific button that needs to be clicked to save the changes, simulate a click event on that button.

Here’s a simple example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Checkbox Automation</title>
</head>
<body>
    <form id="checkboxForm">
        <input type="checkbox" name="item1"> Item 1<br>
        <input type="checkbox" name="item2"> Item 2<br>
        <input type="checkbox" name="item3"> Item 3<br>
        <!-- Add more checkboxes as needed -->
        <button type="button" onclick="saveChanges()">Save Changes</button>
    </form>

    <script>
        function selectAllCheckboxes() {
            // Select all checkboxes
            const checkboxes = document.querySelectorAll('input[type="checkbox"]');

            // Check each checkbox
            checkboxes.forEach(checkbox => {
                checkbox.checked = true;
            });
        }

        function saveChanges() {
            // Select all checkboxes
            selectAllCheckboxes();

            // Optionally, you can add code here to submit the form or perform other actions
            alert("All checkboxes have been selected and saved.");
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

